        {
            "author_association": "NONE",
            "body": "It would give a visual cue that you can use to verify that the correct region is deleted. Having the visual cue will let you know immediately how good your `d#w` guess is because you're focused on the end of the range to be deleted. Atm the change is instantaneous and you have to refocus to the beginning of the deleted region and reread the text to check if what you did is ok. \r\n\r\nThis visual cuing is something that is benefitial to the approach of Kakoune to invert the editor syntax into object + verb, i.e. to cite their [Improving on the editing model](https://kakoune.org/why-kakoune/why-kakoune.html):\r\n\r\n> Kakoune’s grammar is object followed by verb, combined with instantaneous feedback, that means you always see the current object [...] before you apply your change, which allows you to correct errors on the go.\r\n>\r\n> [...] Because of the verb followed by object grammar, vi changes are made in the dark, we don’t see their effect until the whole editing sentence is finished. 5dw will delete to next five words, if you then realize that was one word too many, you need to undo, go back to your initial position, and try again with 4dw. \r\n\r\nSticking in the right number in the `d#w` is not easily done on the first try if you want to do it fast. If you guess low then you can do a couple of `dw`-s to compensate, but guessing high forces you to `u` and then try again. Although this feature would not change the need to undo and retry when wrong, it will make it easier.\r\n",
